04479nam a22005895i 9780520382398DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212021cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2020030583  a9780520382398  a(DE-B1597)566923  a(OCoLC)1178868056  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDR576 7aHIS0550002bisacsh1 aPhilliou, Christine M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTurkey :bA Past Against History /cChristine M. Philliou. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (294 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNote on Transliteration -- tTimeline -- tIntroduction -- t1. Against Power? (1888–1909) -- t2. The Contradictions of Ottoman Constitutionalism and the Remaking of Muhalefet (1908–1913) -- t3. The Joke (1913–1918) -- t4. The True Face of Istanbul (1918–1922) -- t5. Muhalefet from Abroad (1922–1927) -- t6. There Is a World Underground (1928–1945) -- t7. Muhalefet in the Free World (1945–1965) -- tEpilogue -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom its earliest days, the dominant history of the Turkish Republic was told as a triumphant narrative of national self-determination and secular democratic modernization. In that officially sanctioned account, the years between the fall of the Ottoman Empire and the formation of the Turkish state marked an absolute rupture, and the Turkish nation forms an absolute unity. In recent years, this hermetic division has begun to erode—but as the old consensus collapses, new histories and accounts of political authority have been slow to take its place. In this richly detailed alternative history of Turkey, Christine Philliou focuses on the notion of political opposition and dissent—muhalefet—to weave together the Ottoman and Turkish periods. Taking the perennial dissident Refik Halid Karay (1888–1965) as a subject, guide, and interlocutor, she traces the fissures within the Ottoman and modern Turkish elite that bridge the Ottoman Empire and Republican Turkey. Exploring Karay’s political and literary writings across four regimes and two stints in exile, along with his direct confrontation with Mustafa Kemal Atatürk at a crucial moment in 1919, Philliou upends the official history of Turkey and offers new dimensions to our understanding of its political authority and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPolitical culturezTurkeyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073915240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052038239840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520382398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520382398/original  a978-3-11-073915-2  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075408-7  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2021  aZDB-23-DGGb2021